@page "/contract"
@model ApartamentosRenta.Pages.Contract.IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Residential Lease Agreement";
}

<article class="contract-page">
    <header class="contract-header">
        <p class="contract-brand">Premier Property Hub</p>
        <h1>Residential Lease Agreement</h1>
        <p class="contract-subtitle">Apartment rental · United States</p>
        <p class="contract-effective">Effective upon execution by Landlord and Tenant</p>
    </header>

    <div class="contract-notice">
        <strong>Important:</strong> This agreement is a standard residential lease template for apartment rentals in the United States.
        State and local laws (including security-deposit limits, notice periods, and habitability rules) may vary.
        Both parties should review applicable statutes before signing. This document does not constitute legal advice.
    </div>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>1. Parties &amp; Premises</h2>
        <p>
            This Residential Lease Agreement (“Agreement”) is entered into between
            <span class="contract-blank">Premier Property Hub / ___________________________</span> (“Landlord”)
            and <span class="contract-blank">___________________________</span> (“Tenant”).
        </p>
        <p>
            Landlord leases to Tenant the residential unit located at
            <span class="contract-blank">___________________________</span>,
            Unit <span class="contract-blank">_____</span>,
            <span class="contract-blank">City, State, ZIP</span> (“Premises”), for use solely as a private residence.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>2. Term</h2>
        <p>
            The lease term begins on <span class="contract-blank">__ / __ / ____</span>
            and ends on <span class="contract-blank">__ / __ / ____</span>,
            unless terminated earlier in accordance with this Agreement or applicable law.
            Holdover tenancy, if any, shall be month-to-month on the same terms unless otherwise agreed in writing.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>3. Rent</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Monthly rent: <span class="contract-blank">$________</span>, due on the <span class="contract-blank">___</span> day of each month.</li>
            <li>Payment method: Zelle, certified check, money order, or other method approved by Landlord in writing.</li>
            <li>Rent is late if not received by <span class="contract-blank">11:59 p.m.</span> on the due date.</li>
            <li>Late fee: <span class="contract-blank">$________</span> or the maximum amount permitted by applicable state law, whichever is less.</li>
            <li>Returned payment fee: <span class="contract-blank">$________</span>, plus any bank charges, where allowed by law.</li>
            <li>Prorated rent applies for partial months at move-in or move-out unless otherwise agreed.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>4. Security Deposit</h2>
        <p>
            Tenant shall pay a security deposit of <span class="contract-blank">$________</span> before occupancy.
            The security deposit is not rent and may not be applied as the last month’s rent unless Landlord agrees in writing.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>The deposit secures Tenant’s performance of all obligations under this Agreement.</li>
            <li>Landlord may deduct for unpaid rent, late fees (if permitted), damages beyond normal wear and tear, cleaning required to restore the unit to move-in condition, and other lawful charges.</li>
            <li>Landlord shall return the balance of the deposit, with an itemized statement of deductions, within the time required by applicable state and local law (commonly 14–30 days after move-out and surrender of keys).</li>
            <li>Where required by law, the deposit shall be held in a separate interest-bearing or non-interest-bearing account as mandated by the governing jurisdiction.</li>
            <li>Normal wear and tear (e.g., minor scuffs, fading paint from ordinary use) is not chargeable to Tenant.</li>
            <li>Tenant must provide a forwarding address in writing at move-out. Failure to do so may delay return only to the extent permitted by law.</li>
            <li>Pre-move-out inspection may be offered where required or requested under local habitability or deposit-return statutes.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>5. Visit &amp; Application Deposit</h2>
        <p>
            Any non-refundable visit, application, or holding fee shall be disclosed separately in writing before payment.
            Refundable visit deposits paid via Zelle or other approved method may be credited toward the security deposit or first month’s rent upon execution of this Agreement, if stated in the payment receipt or addendum.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>6. Cell Phones, Wireless Devices &amp; Telecommunications</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Tenant may use personal cell phones, tablets, and other wireless devices within the Premises in compliance with federal, state, and local law.</li>
            <li>Landlord does not guarantee cellular signal strength, data coverage, or internet availability inside the unit or building.</li>
            <li>Tenant shall not install external antennas, satellite dishes, signal boosters, or repeaters without Landlord’s prior written consent and compliance with FCC rules (47 C.F.R. Part 1 and applicable OTARD restrictions where relevant).</li>
            <li>No drilling, mounting, or wiring for personal devices may damage walls, windows, common areas, or building infrastructure. Tenant is responsible for repair costs caused by unauthorized installations.</li>
            <li>Ring tones, speakerphone use, and device volume must not disturb neighbors or violate quiet-hours rules in Section 12.</li>
            <li>Tenant is solely responsible for all charges from mobile carriers and third-party service providers.</li>
            <li>Landlord may provide building Wi‑Fi or wired internet only if listed in a separate addendum; otherwise Tenant must arrange service independently where permitted.</li>
            <li>Recording audio or video of other residents or staff in common areas without consent may violate state wiretap or privacy laws and is prohibited.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>7. Utilities &amp; Services</h2>
        <p>Unless stated below, Tenant is responsible for activating and paying all utilities and services.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Landlord pays: <span class="contract-blank">water / trash / __________</span></li>
            <li>Tenant pays: <span class="contract-blank">electric / gas / internet / __________</span></li>
            <li>Tenant shall not allow utilities to be disconnected for non-payment while occupying the Premises.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>8. Use, Occupancy &amp; Compliance</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Maximum occupants: <span class="contract-blank">_____</span> persons unless approved in writing.</li>
            <li>No illegal activity, short-term subletting (e.g., Airbnb), or commercial use unless authorized.</li>
            <li>Tenant shall comply with building rules, fire codes, HOA/condo regulations (if any), and all applicable federal, state, and local laws, including fair housing and anti-discrimination statutes.</li>
            <li>Smoke and carbon monoxide detectors must remain installed and functional; Tenant shall test devices and report malfunctions promptly.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>9. Maintenance &amp; Repairs</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Tenant shall keep the Premises clean and sanitary and promptly report maintenance issues, leaks, pests, or safety hazards.</li>
            <li>Landlord shall maintain structural components, plumbing, heating, and systems required for habitability under applicable landlord-tenant law, except where damage is caused by Tenant, guests, or pets.</li>
            <li>Tenant is responsible for minor consumables (light bulbs, batteries, filters) and damage caused by misuse or neglect.</li>
            <li>Emergency repairs: contact Landlord at <span class="contract-blank">___________________________</span>. For life-threatening emergencies, call 911 first.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>10. Landlord Entry</h2>
        <p>
            Landlord may enter the Premises for inspections, repairs, showings to prospective tenants or buyers, or other lawful purposes
            with reasonable notice as required by state law (typically 24–48 hours), except in emergencies where immediate entry is permitted.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>11. Pets, Smoking &amp; Alterations</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Pets: <span class="contract-blank">Not permitted / Permitted with written approval and deposit of $________</span>.</li>
            <li>Service and assistance animals: reasonable accommodation requests will be handled in accordance with the Fair Housing Act and applicable state law.</li>
            <li>Smoking, vaping, and marijuana use are prohibited inside the unit and common areas unless expressly allowed by law and Landlord in writing.</li>
            <li>No painting, structural changes, or alterations without Landlord’s written consent.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>12. Quiet Enjoyment &amp; Nuisance</h2>
        <p>
            Tenant shall not create excessive noise, odors, or disturbances between
            <span class="contract-blank">10:00 p.m.</span> and <span class="contract-blank">8:00 a.m.</span>
            or at any time that unreasonably interferes with neighbors’ quiet enjoyment.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>13. Insurance</h2>
        <p>
            Landlord’s insurance does not cover Tenant’s personal property. Tenant is strongly encouraged to maintain renter’s insurance covering personal belongings, liability, and additional living expenses.
            Minimum liability coverage of <span class="contract-blank">$100,000</span> may be required where permitted by law.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>14. Default &amp; Remedies</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Events of default include non-payment of rent, material breach of this Agreement, illegal conduct, or abandonment.</li>
            <li>Upon default, Landlord may pursue remedies available under applicable law, including notice to cure, termination, possession proceedings, and collection of lawful damages.</li>
            <li>Attorney’s fees and court costs may be recovered by the prevailing party only where authorized by state statute or this Agreement.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>15. Move-Out &amp; Surrender</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Tenant shall provide written notice as required by law before terminating a month-to-month tenancy or vacating at end of term.</li>
            <li>Upon move-out, Tenant shall return all keys, remotes, and access devices; remove personal property; and leave the unit broom-clean.</li>
            <li>Abandoned property may be handled according to state abandoned-property laws.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>16. Required Disclosures (U.S.)</h2>
        <p>Where applicable under federal or state law, Landlord shall provide separate written disclosures, including but not limited to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Lead-based paint disclosure (pre-1978 housing, 42 U.S.C. § 4852d)</li>
            <li>Mold, bedbug, or pest history where required locally</li>
            <li>Flood zone or natural hazard disclosures (state-specific)</li>
            <li>Security deposit receipt and banking information where required</li>
            <li>Move-in / move-out condition checklist where required</li>
            <li>Landlord/agent identity and address for legal notices</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section">
        <h2>17. Governing Law &amp; Entire Agreement</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>This Agreement is governed by the laws of the State of <span class="contract-blank">___________________________</span>, without regard to conflict-of-law rules.</li>
            <li>Any provision invalid under applicable law shall be severed; remaining terms stay in effect.</li>
            <li>This document, together with signed addenda, constitutes the entire agreement and supersedes prior oral or written understandings.</li>
            <li>Amendments must be in writing and signed by both parties.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="contract-section contract-signatures">
        <h2>18. Signatures</h2>
        <p>By signing below, each party agrees to all terms of this Residential Lease Agreement.</p>
        <div class="signature-grid">
            <div class="signature-block">
                <p class="signature-line"></p>
                <p>Landlord / Authorized Agent</p>
                <p>Date: <span class="contract-blank">__ / __ / ____</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="signature-block">
                <p class="signature-line"></p>
                <p>Tenant</p>
                <p>Date: <span class="contract-blank">__ / __ / ____</span></p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="contract-footer">
        <p>Premier Property Hub · Residential Lease Agreement · <a href="/contract">/contract</a></p>
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm mt-2" onclick="window.print()">Print contract</button>
    </footer>
</article>
